05962nam a22008415i 9780231549691DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020012997  a97802315496917 a10.7312/gran192162doi  a(DE-B1597)566477  a(OCoLC)1229161524  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aTD195.E4bG73 2020 4aTD195.E4bG73 2020 7aSCI0920002bisacsh04a363.738/7412231 aGrant, Don, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSuper Polluters :bTackling the World’s Largest Sites of Climate-Disrupting Emissions /cAndrew Jorgenson, Don Grant, Wesley Longhofer. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSociety and the Environment00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Who Is Responsible for This Mess?: The Climate Crisis and Hyperemitting Power Plants -- t2. Cleaning Up Their Act: Potential Emission Reductions from Targeting the Worst of the Worst Power Plants -- t3. Recipes for Disaster: How Social Structures Interact to Make Environmentally Destructive Plants Even More So -- t4. A Win-Win Solution?: The Paradoxical Effects of Efficiency on Plants’ CO2 Emissions -- t5. Bottom-Up Strategies: The Effectiveness of Local Policies and Activism (with Ion Bogdan Vasi) -- t6. Next Steps: Future Research and Action on Society’s Super Polluters -- tAppendixes -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPower plants are essential to achieving the standard of living that modern societies demand and the social and economic infrastructure on which they depend. Yet their indispensability has allowed them to evade responsibility for their vast carbon emissions. Fossil-fueled power plants are the single largest sites of anthropogenic greenhouse gases, making them one of the greatest threats to our planet’s climate. Significant as they are, we lack a comprehensive understanding of the social causes that enable power plant emissions and continue to delay their reduction.Super Polluters offers a groundbreaking global analysis of carbon pollution caused by the generation of electricity, pinpointing who bears the most responsibility for the energy sector’s vast emissions and what can be done about them. The sociologists Don Grant, Andrew Jorgenson, and Wesley Longhofer analyze a novel dataset on the carbon dioxide emissions and structural attributes of thousands of fossil-fueled power plants around the world, identifying which plants discharge the most carbon. They investigate the global, organizational, and political conditions that explain these hyper-emitting facilities’ behavior and call into question the claim that improvements in technical efficiency will always reduce emissions. Grant, Jorgenson, and Longhofer demonstrate which energy and climate policies are most effective at abating power-plant pollution, emphasizing how mobilized citizen activism shapes those outcomes. A comprehensive account of who bears the blame for our warming planet, Super Polluters points to more feasible and effective emission reduction strategies that target the world’s most profligate polluters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAirxPollution. 0aCarbon dioxide mitigation. 0aElectric power-plantsxEnvironmental aspects. 0aEnvironmental sociology. 7aSCIENCE / Global Warming & Climate Change.2bisacsh  aclimate change.  aenvironmental sociology.  apollution.  apower plants.1 aJorgenson, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLonghofer, Wesley, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part o